---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const costs = [
  {
    title: 'ilo',
    price: '$0',
    body: 'The CLI, local MCP server, website, and Worker API are open source under the MIT license.',
  },
  {
    title: 'X API',
    price: 'Your plan',
    body: 'Connect your own X developer app. Any usage limits or charges are between you and X.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Cloudflare',
    price: 'Optional',
    body: 'You only need Cloudflare if you deploy your own copy of the public site and tool API.',
  },
]
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Pricing"
  description="ilo is free and MIT licensed. Bring your own X developer account and optional Cloudflare deployment."
>
  <main class="site-frame py-16">
    <section class="max-w-2xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-medium text-primary">No SaaS plans</p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 text-pretty text-4xl font-medium -tracking-[0.6px] text-foreground">
        Free software. Your infrastructure.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-pretty text-xl/8 text-foreground-muted">
        ilo has no subscriptions, usage credits, hosted accounts, or paid
        reports. Install it locally, fork it, or deploy it yourself.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12 grid gap-3 md:grid-cols-3">
      {costs.map((item) => (
        <article class="rounded-lg bg-muted p-6">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-foreground-muted">{item.title}</p>
          <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-semibold text-foreground">{item.price}</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-foreground-muted">{item.body}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </section>

    <section class="mt-14 max-w-2xl border-t border-border pt-10">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-medium text-foreground">What free includes</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-base leading-7 text-foreground-muted">
        <p>
          The MIT-licensed repository includes the CLI, local MCP server,
          scheduling and publishing code, documentation site, report guides,
          and public tool API. You can use it commercially, modify it, or ship
          your own version under the terms of the license.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is no ilo account to create and no usage meter in the local
          software. Drafts and schedules stay on your machine. Your MCP client
          starts ilo locally and publishing goes directly through the X app you
          connect.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-medium text-foreground">Costs you may still have</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-base leading-7 text-foreground-muted">
        <p>
          X decides which developer plan and limits are required for publishing.
          Check its current pricing before connecting an app. ilo does not add a
          fee or resell that access.
        </p>
        <p>
          Running the CLI and local MCP server does not require Cloudflare. A
          Cloudflare account is only needed when you want your own hosted copy
          of the website and tool API. Your bill then depends on your traffic,
          bindings, and Cloudflare plan.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-medium text-foreground">Public ilo.so tools</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-foreground-muted">
        The tools on ilo.so are available without an account, but they may be
        cached, rate limited, changed, or unavailable. Self-host the Worker if
        another application needs controlled capacity or a stable deployment.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-medium text-foreground">Common questions</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-base leading-7 text-foreground-muted">
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-foreground">Can I use ilo for client work?</strong>
          Yes. The MIT license permits commercial use. You remain responsible
          for provider terms, connected accounts, published content, and any
          infrastructure you operate.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-foreground">Can I pay for a hosted ilo plan?</strong>
          No. There are no hosted accounts, analytics subscriptions, credits,
          or one-off paid reports. The public report library is free to read.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-foreground">Do I need an X API plan to read the site?</strong>
          No. It is only needed for CLI actions that use your own X developer
          app, such as publishing a post.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-medium text-foreground">Support the project</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-foreground-muted">
        If ilo saves you time, star the repository, contribute a fix, or sponsor
        Ian. Sponsorship supports maintenance without turning the tool back into
        a subscription product. It does not unlock a private tier or priority
        API access; the same source and features remain available to everyone.
        Bug reports, documentation fixes, and tested provider contributions are
        useful ways to help even if you do not sponsor the project.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          class="inline-flex h-10 items-center rounded-lg bg-primary px-5 text-sm font-medium text-primary-foreground hover:bg-primary-hover"
          href="https://github.com/iannuttall/ilo"
        >
          View on GitHub
        </a>
        <a
          class="inline-flex h-10 items-center rounded-lg bg-secondary px-5 text-sm font-medium text-secondary-foreground hover:bg-secondary-hover"
          href="https://github.com/sponsors/iannuttall"
        >
          Sponsor Ian
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
